    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b5fae31b-e184-407d-993d-01787195b3b4",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an 8-year-old boy who appears tired but non-toxic, sitting restlessly on the exam table with a box of tissues in his lap. He has a runny nose with clear to slightly cloudy discharge, frequent sneezing, and mild redness around the nostrils from repeated wiping. His voice sounds slightly nasal, and he occasionally coughs to clear postnasal drip. He is alert, interactive, and able to answer questions appropriately for his age, though he seems more clingy than usual and complains that his throat feels “scratchy.”\n\nHe lives with his parents and a younger sister in a suburban home and attends primary school in the third grade. {patientName} usually enjoys playing soccer after school, riding his bike with neighborhood friends, and building elaborate structures with toy blocks and craft supplies. Over the last 2 days, he has skipped soccer practice because of fatigue, nasal congestion, and poor sleep due to nighttime stuffiness. His appetite is slightly decreased, but he is still drinking fluids and asking for simple foods like toast, soup, and fruit.\n\nAt home, {patientName}'s family describes him as generally healthy and active, with no chronic respiratory disease. He has had multiple school exposures during the winter term, including several classmates with colds. His mother reports that he developed sneezing and rhinorrhea first, followed by congestion, mild sore throat, and a low-grade fever. He has no shortness of breath, no wheezing, and no difficulty swallowing.\n\nSocially, {patientName} is well supported by family and friends. He has a close relationship with his grandparents, who help with after-school care, and he enjoys weekend visits to the park and children’s museum. His illness has mainly affected sleep, school concentration, and play activity, but he remains hydrated, conversational, and generally comfortable between bouts of congestion and coughing."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d4978ca1-8ac0-48d8-a98f-f95fe0abf87d",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no significant past medical history and has been meeting developmental milestones appropriately. He was born at term without neonatal complications and has not required prior hospitalizations. He has had routine childhood viral illnesses but no history of asthma, recurrent pneumonia, or chronic sinus disease. Immunizations are up to date for age.\n\nHis parents report intermittent seasonal allergic rhinitis during spring, usually presenting with sneezing and itchy eyes, but his current illness is different because of sore throat, malaise, and low-grade fever after exposure to sick classmates. He has no history of medication intolerance apart from mild stomach upset with some antibiotics in the past, and no known food-triggered anaphylaxis. He is not exposed to tobacco smoke in the home.\n\nLifestyle history is notable for regular physical activity through school recess, soccer, and outdoor play. His diet is generally balanced, although like many children his age, he prefers snacks and sweet cereals if given the choice. Sleep is normally adequate, but current nasal obstruction has caused nighttime awakenings over the last two nights. There is no recent travel, no known COVID-era quarantine concerns at present, and no exposure to pets or environmental irritants beyond typical seasonal pollen."
          }
        ]
      }
